{{Infobox book | italic title =no | name = Teaching with'' Calvin and Hobbes | image = Teaching with Calvin and Hobbes 1993 Linda Holmen Mary Santella-Johnson Bill Watterson textbook cover by Jan Roebken.jpg | caption = | author = Linda Holmen, Mary Santella-Johnson, [[Bill Watterson]] | illustrator = Jan Roebken, Bill Watterson | cover_artist = Jan Roebken | country = United States | language = English | subject = [[Speech and language pathology]] | genre = Children's textbook | publisher = Playground Publishing | pub_date = 1993 | media_type = Print ([[Paperback]]) | pages = 200 | isbn = 1-878849-15-8 | oclc = 29340469 | dewey = | congress = | preceded_by = | followed_by = }} '''''Teaching with'' Calvin and Hobbes''' is an American children's [[textbook]] published in 1993. As a rare piece of officially licensed ''[[Calvin and Hobbes]]'' merchandise, it is a highly valued [[collectible]].
==Content== Written by a [[speech-language pathologist]] and a [[learning disabilities]] educator, ''Teaching with'' Calvin and Hobbes is a language textbook for elementary and intermediate-level students.<ref name="holmen1993">{{cite book |last1=Holmen |first1=Linda |last2=Santella-Johnson |first2=Mary |last3=Watterson |first3=Bill |authorlink3=Bill Watterson |others=Cover and supplementary art by Jan Roebken |title=Teaching with Calvin and Hobbes |year=1993 |publisher=Playground Publishing |location=Fargo, North Dakota |isbn=1-878849-15-8 |laysummary=http://ignatz.brinkster.net/cteaching.html |laydate=2004}}</ref><ref name="minotdaily1993">{{cite news |title=Reading with Calvin |url=http://bp2.blogger.com/_qg3f_YdsdGg/SGh1s6xp4vI/AAAAAAAAABM/XHj2S6XIVsA/s1600-h/Minot+Daily+News+1993+Nov+16+Teaching+with+Calvin+and+Hobbes.jpg |format=jpg |newspaper=[[Minot Daily News]] |location=Minot, North Dakota |date=1993-11-16 |page=1 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150823054057/http://bp2.blogger.com/_qg3f_YdsdGg/SGh1s6xp4vI/AAAAAAAAABM/XHj2S6XIVsA/s1600-h/Minot+Daily+News+1993+Nov+16+Teaching+with+Calvin+and+Hobbes.jpg |archivedate=2015-08-23 |deadurl=no |accessdate=2015-08-23 |quote=[''Teaching with Calvin and Hobbes''] is for teaching reading to students in grades four to nine. Holmen and Santella-Johnson began using the cartoon characters with children who have learning disabilities and language disorders. They found the students identified with Calvin, Holmen said.}}</ref> Jan Roebken created the cover and additional interior illustrations.<ref name="holmen1993" />
The book reprints fifty-seven ''Calvin and Hobbes'' [[comic strips]], organized into five lesson units. Each unit begins with a series of comic strips that form a story. The five units are:
# "The Binoculars" – [[Calvin (Calvin and Hobbes)|Calvin]] breaks his father's binoculars and solicits [[Hobbes (Calvin and Hobbes)|Hobbes]]' advice. # "The Find" – Calvin discovers and assembles a [[dinosaur]] skeleton, of sorts. Hobbes renders a drawing of the creature. # "The Christmas Story" – As Calvin struggles to be good in anticipation of [[Santa]]'s arrival, he and Hobbes discuss the [[philosophy of law]] and the nature of [[belief]]. # "The Bug Collection" – Calvin forgets to do his homework, and rushes to complete it on the way to school. [[Secondary characters in Calvin and Hobbes#Susie Derkins|Susie]] gets sent to the principal's office. # "The Report" – Calvin and Susie are assigned a joint homework project.
In each unit, questions for [[reading comprehension|comprehension]] and [[collaborative learning|discussion]] follow the comic strips:
{{quotation| * Do you think Calvin's mother should have told Calvin the truth about his dinosaur? Why or why not? [...] * Imagining and creating are important and fun, but, when it goes too far, it's time to get back to reality. Do you think Calvin was disappointed when his mother brought him back to reality or do you think he always had an inkling that he was having fun with his [[imagination]]? * Can you think of a time when you were imagining or creating and your mom or dad brought you back to reality? * Were you disappointed to get back to reality?<ref name="holmen1993" />}}
In both the 1996 first edition and the 2006 second edition of their book ''How to Reach and Teach All Children in the Inclusive Classroom'', teachers Sandra F. Rief and Julie A. Heimburge "highly recommend" ''Teaching with' Calvin and Hobbes as an [[educational]] resource.<ref name="rief1996">{{cite book |last1=Rief |first1=Sandra F. |last2=Heimburge |first2=Julie A. |title=How To Reach & Teach All Students in the Inclusive Classroom: Ready-to-Use Strategies, Lessons and Activities for Teaching Students with Diverse Learning Needs |edition=1st |year=1996 |publisher=[[Jossey-Bass]] |isbn=978-0-87628-399-8 |page=268 |quote=There is a wonderful book called ''Teaching with Calvin and Hobbes'' by Mary Santella-Johnson and Linda Holmen that we highly recommend.}}</ref><ref name="rief2006">{{cite book |last1=Rief |first1=Sandra F. |last2=Heimburge |first2=Julie A. |title=How To Reach and Teach All Children in the Inclusive Classroom: Practical Strategies, Lessons, and Activities |edition=2nd |year=2006 |publisher=[[Jossey-Bass]] |isbn=978-0-7879-8154-9 |page=210 |quote=We highly recommend a wonderful book, ''Teaching with Calvin and Hobbes''...}}</ref>
==Rarity== {{See also|Calvin and Hobbes#Merchandising}}
[[File:Chester Fritz Library summer.jpg|thumb|left|250px|The [[Chester Fritz Library]] in North Dakota preserves a copy of ''Teaching wit''h Calvin and Hobbes.]]
Owing to [[Bill Watterson]]'s principled refusal to license his comic strip for merchandise in general,<ref name="watterson1989">{{cite conference |url=http://ignatz.brinkster.net/cheapening.html |title=What We Expect of the Comics (The Cheapening of the Comics) |first=Bill |last=Watterson |authorlink=Bill Watterson |date=1989-10-27 |conference=The 1989 Festival of Cartoon Art |conferenceurl=http://cartoons.osu.edu/FCA/1989/about.php |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150112182422/http://ignatz.brinkster.net/cheapening.html |archivedate=2015-01-12 |deadurl=yes |accessdate=2015-08-23 |quote=Characters lose their believability as they start endorsing major companies and lend their faces to bedsheets and boxer shorts. The appealing innocence and sincerity of cartoon characters is corrupted when they use those qualities to peddle products. |df= }}</ref><ref name="watterson1995">{{cite book |last=Watterson |first=Bill |authorlink=Bill Watterson |title=The Calvin and Hobbes Tenth Anniversary Book |year=1995 |publisher=[[Andrews McMeel Publishing]] |isbn=978-0-8362-0438-4 |pages=10–12 |quote=...I don't want some greeting card company using Calvin to wish people a happy anniversary...}}</ref> ''Teaching with'' Calvin and Hobbes is an exceptional item; a license was granted to the authors after they personally communicated to Watterson the success they had using his comic strip to teach children with learning disabilities.<ref name="holmen1993" /><ref name="hulsizer">{{cite web |url=http://ignatz.brinkster.net/citems.html |title=A Concise Guide To All Legal Calvin and Hobbes Items |last=Hulsizer |first=Tim |work=Calvin and Hobbes: Magic on Paper |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150430000955/http://ignatz.brinkster.net/citems.html |archivedate=2015-04-30 |deadurl=no |accessdate=2015-08-23 |quote=''Teaching with Calvin and Hobbes'': This is a teaching book licensed specially by the syndicate and Bill Watterson.}}</ref>
Published in a limited [[print run]] in [[Fargo, North Dakota]],<ref name="holmen1993" /> ''Teaching with Calvin and Hobbes'' is a very rare and highly sought-after book.<ref name="grzegorek2010">{{cite web |url=http://www.clevescene.com/scene-and-heard/archives/2010/08/31/expanded-book-chronicles-search-for-bill-watterson-calvin-and-hobbes-creator |title=Expanded Book Chronicles Search for Bill Watterson, Calvin and Hobbes Creator |last1=Grzegorek |first1=Vince |last2=Ferris |first2=D.X. |date=2010-08-31 |work=Scene and Heard: Cleveland Scene's News Blog |publisher=[[Cleveland Scene]] |location=Cleveland, Ohio |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131013200426/http://www.clevescene.com/scene-and-heard/archives/2010/08/31/expanded-book-chronicles-search-for-bill-watterson-calvin-and-hobbes-creator |archivedate=2013-10-13 |deadurl=no |accessdate=2015-08-23 |quote=...the über-rare ''Teaching with Calvin and Hobbes''...}}</ref><ref name="murphy2011">{{cite web |url=https://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,2817,2384102,00.asp |title=Amazon Algorithm Price War Leads to $23.6-Million-Dollar Book Listing |last=Murphy |first=David |date=2011-04-23 |work=[[PC Magazine]] |publisher=[[Ziff Davis]] |location=New York, New York |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150516165120/http://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,2817,2384102,00.asp |archivedate=2015-05-16 |deadurl=no |accessdate=2015-08-23 |quote=...you're trying to hunt down that elusive, rare edition of ''Teaching with Calvin and Hobbes''?}}</ref>
In the 2010 revised edition of his book ''Looking for Calvin and Hobbes: The Unconventional Story of Bill Watterson and His Revolutionary Comic Strip'', Nevin Martell says that only after a long search did he obtain a copy of ''Teaching with'' Calvin and Hobbes, that copies of the book sell for very high prices, and that the book is "perhaps the most difficult piece of official ''Calvin and Hobbes'' memorabilia to find."<ref name="martell2010">{{cite book |last=Martell |first=Nevin |title=Looking for Calvin and Hobbes: The Unconventional Story of Bill Watterson and His Revolutionary Comic Strip |edition=Revised |year=2010 |publisher=[[Continuum Books]] |isbn=978-1-4411-0685-8 |page=236}}</ref>
The book price comparison website Dualj.com, which tracked sale prices of books, recorded that a copy of ''Teaching with'' Calvin and Hobbes sold for US$10,000 in 2009.<ref name="dualj2010">{{cite web |url=http://www.dualj.com/item_full.aspx?itemid=1878849158 |title=Teaching with Calvin and Hobbes: Book Price Comparison History |date=2010-05-20 |publisher=Dualj.com |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110423031257/http://www.dualj.com/ |archivedate=2011-04-23 |deadurl=yes |accessdate=2011-12-26}}</ref><ref name="tracking2010">{{cite web |url=http://teachingwithcalvinandhobbes.blogspot.com/2010/05/book-price-comparison-history-is-posted.html |title=Book Price Comparison History is posted at Dualj |date=2010-05-20 |work=Teaching with Calvin and Hobbes: Tracking the Book |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131202221755/http://teachingwithcalvinandhobbes.blogspot.com/2010/05/book-price-comparison-history-is-posted.html |archivedate=2013-12-02 |deadurl=no |accessdate=2015-08-23}}</ref> Valuations for the book ranged to US$34,000 in 2012.<ref name="yung2012">{{cite web |url=http://www.doobybrain.com/2012/05/24/teaching-with-calvin-hobbes-one-of-the-rarest-and-most-expensive-textbooks-ever-published/ |title=Teaching with Calvin & Hobbes: one of the rarest and most expensive textbooks ever published |last=Yung |first=Herman |date=2012-05-24 |publisher=Doobybrain.com |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150810102928/http://www.doobybrain.com/2012/05/24/teaching-with-calvin-hobbes-one-of-the-rarest-and-most-expensive-textbooks-ever-published/ |archivedate=2015-08-10 |deadurl=no |accessdate=2015-08-23}}</ref> A copy was sold on [[eBay]] for an "extremely generous" donation to the [[HALO Trust]] charity in 2013.<ref name="ebay1">{{cite web |url=http://www.ebay.com/itm/for-Charity-TEACHING-WITH-CALVIN-AND-HOBBES-Reading-Textbook-Bill-Watterson-HALO-/370843195721 |title=for Charity TEACHING WITH CALVIN AND HOBBES Reading Textbook Bill Watterson HALO |date=2013-08-04 |publisher=[[eBay]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150907175510/http://www.ebay.com/itm/for-Charity-TEACHING-WITH-CALVIN-AND-HOBBES-Reading-Textbook-Bill-Watterson-HALO-/370843195721 |archivedate=2015-09-07 |deadurl=no |accessdate=2015-09-07}}</ref><ref name="ebay2">{{cite web |url=http://www.ebay.com/itm/TEACHING-WITH-CALVIN-AND-HOBBES-Bill-Watterson-Comics-Rare-School-Text-Book-1-Ed-/370843194557 |title=TEACHING WITH CALVIN AND HOBBES Bill Watterson Comics Rare School Text Book 1 Ed |publisher=[[eBay]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150907172737/http://www.ebay.com/itm/TEACHING-WITH-CALVIN-AND-HOBBES-Bill-Watterson-Comics-Rare-School-Text-Book-1-Ed-/370843194557 |archivedate=2015-09-07 |deadurl=no |accessdate=2015-09-07 |quote=Update August 2013: I sold my personal copy, as described hereunder, for an extremely generous donation to The HALO Trust.}}</ref>
[[WorldCat]] lists only eight libraries in the entire world as holding a copy of the book: the United States [[Library of Congress]], the [[Chester Fritz Library]] along with only three other libraries in [[North Dakota]] (where the book was published), and one university library each in [[Ohio]], [[California]], and [[Singapore]].<ref name="worldcat">{{cite web |url=http://www.worldcat.org/title/teaching-with-calvin-and-hobbes/oclc/29340469 |title=Teaching with Calvin and Hobbes: Find a copy in the library |work=[[WorldCat]] |publisher=[[Online Computer Library Center]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150823061810/http://www.worldcat.org/title/teaching-with-calvin-and-hobbes/oclc/29340469 |archivedate=2015-08-23 |deadurl=no |accessdate=2015-08-23}}</ref> The Chester Fritz Library at the [[University of North Dakota]] preserves its copy of ''Teaching with'' Calvin and Hobbes in the library's Special Collections Department for rare publications and manuscripts.<ref name="chesterfritz">{{cite web |url=http://odin-primo.hosted.exlibrisgroup.com/primo_library/libweb/action/dlSearch.do?vid=und&institution=und&onCampus=false&group=GUEST&dym=true&search_scope=all&query=any,contains,%22Teaching+with+Calvin+and+Hobbes%22 |title=''Teaching with Calvin and Hobbes'' in the Chester Fritz Library |publisher=[[University of North Dakota]] |location=Grand Forks, North Dakota |accessdate=2015-08-23 |quote=Location: UND Special Collections CFL Floor 4 Special Collections Rare Books; Item Status: Non-circulating}}</ref>
